<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. An Account of Lake Superior, 1807-1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0037</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">Phenomenon merits.  The old Inhabitants say the term is seven years but of this there is no possitive proof.  The beach from the last mentioned Point is much lower than the sandy mountain being seldom more than 20 or 30 feet above the level of the lake and has nothing remarkable except a small vein of fine freestone beautifully tinged with red, blue, and green, which is about two leagues from the Point and one, to the commencement of the precipices called by the French the Portails ou Façades.  Here the coast tends more to the west and begins gradually to rise from ten to at least 200 feet; the rock is a white freestone perfectly perpendicular, and in a distance of three leagues has three little Bays nearly at equal distances placed by the hand of Providence to insure safety of a coast otherwise not to be attempted in almost any season or circumstances.</p>
